[normal]Introduction.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]We welcomed the Committee’s Fourth Report on “Cost of Motor Insura
[normal]nce: Whiplash” released on 
[normal]31
[normal]st
[normal] July 2013
[normal]. Whilst there were some points upon which we disagreed, we saw the overall response as both balanced and pragmatic. We have also seen Mrs 
[normal]Ellman’s
[normal] letter of 29
[normal]th
[normal] October to the Secretary of State for Justice. We concur that whilst the Government’s own response to the whiplash issue should be broadly welcomed, that response was light on detail and timeframes. Certain key points raised were simply not mentioned and 
[normal]as always, our concern is that “the devil will be in the detail”.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We will deal with what we consider to be the key outstanding points in turn:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Conclusions[bold].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We welcome the 
[normal]TSC
[normal]’s continued engagement and scrutiny in this important policy area.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We have articulated our concerns and would welcome the chance to discuss these further with members of the 
[normal]TSC
[normal]. We would also express an over-arching concern in terms of timeframes. We are all of course aware that an Election will take place in May 2015. R
[normal]ealistically therefore, much of this important work will have to be undertaken and delivered against in the next 12 months. The 
[normal]MoJ
[normal] have stated tha
[normal]t they intend to work “at pace”
[normal] - a comment which we welcome.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is now for all stakeholders to support the 
[normal]MoJ
[normal] in their work and to help both the Committee and Government to implement meaningful change which will ultimately benefit the end consumer in the form of reduced motor premiums.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]December 2013
